│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transform \"select Cond, !X, X -> xor Cond, X\" in       │
│ InstCombine is applied when isKnownInversion(FalseVal, TrueVal) holds. This rewrite    │
│ changes the dataflow: the original select only uses one of its operands depending on   │
│ Cond, so poison in the unselected operand does not propagate. The xor rewrite          │
│ unconditionally consumes X, which can introduce poison when X is a                     │
│ potentially-poison-producing instruction (e.g., icmp with samesign). This makes the    │
│ target more poisonous than the source, as shown by Alive2.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's       │
│ Log:\nThe first and only transformation applied is in visitSelectInst: the select is   │
│ rewritten to xor i1 %cond, %cmp2. The reproducer shows %cmp2 is icmp samesign ugt i64  │
│ %x, 10, which can be poison depending on %x. The source select avoided using %cmp2     │
│ when %cond was true; the target xor always uses %cmp2, causing poison.\n\n3. Root      │
│ Cause Analysis:\nThe condition in InstCombineSelect.cpp at lines 4156-4159 is:\n  //   │
│ select Cond, !X, X -> xor Cond, X\n  if (CondVal->getType() == SI.getType() &&         │
│ isKnownInversion(FalseVal, TrueVal))\n    return BinaryOperator::CreateXor(CondVal,    │
│ FalseVal);\nThis ignores the safety of speculatively executing the value substituted   │
│ into xor. If FalseVal is an instruction that is not safe to speculatively execute (can │
│ produce poison/undef in contexts where select would have avoided it), the transform is │
│ illegal under poison semantics. samesign icmp is one such case.\n\n4. Proposed Edit    │
│ Point(s):\nWe should guard the transform with a speculative-execution safety check on  │
│ the value that will be fed to xor. Specifically, only perform the rewrite if FalseVal  │
│ is either a constant or an instruction that isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute. This         │
│ preserves the non-speculative nature of select w.r.t. poison. Edit at                  │
│ InstCombineSelect.cpp line ~4156:\n\n- Before returning the xor, insert:\n  if (auto   │
│ *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(FalseVal))\n    if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I))\n     │
│ return nullptr;\n\nThis ensures we do not introduce unconditional consumption of a     │
│ potentially poison-producing value.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy guarding the select-to-xor   │
│ inversion transform with isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute on the operand substituted into  │
│ xor, we prevent the introduction of extra poison and align with LLVM's semantics that  │
│ select does not speculatively consume unselected operands. This fix addresses the      │
│ incorrect transformation in the given reproducer and similar cases involving           │
│ poison-sensitive compares such as samesign icmp."})                                    │
