│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The transform "select Cond, !X, X -> xor Cond, X" in InstCombine is applied when       │
│ isKnownInversion(FalseVal, TrueVal) holds. This rewrite changes the dataflow: the      │
│ original select only uses one of its operands depending on Cond, so poison in the      │
│ unselected operand does not propagate. The xor rewrite unconditionally consumes X,     │
│ which can introduce poison when X is a potentially-poison-producing instruction (e.g., │
│ icmp with samesign). This makes the target more poisonous than the source, as shown by │
│ Alive2.                                                                                │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The first and only transformation applied is in visitSelectInst: the select is         │
│ rewritten to xor i1 %cond, %cmp2. The reproducer shows %cmp2 is icmp samesign ugt i64  │
│ %x, 10, which can be poison depending on %x. The source select avoided using %cmp2     │
│ when %cond was true; the target xor always uses %cmp2, causing poison.                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ The condition in InstCombineSelect.cpp at lines 4156-4159 is:                          │
│   // select Cond, !X, X -> xor Cond, X                                                 │
│   if (CondVal->getType() == SI.getType() && isKnownInversion(FalseVal, TrueVal))       │
│     return BinaryOperator::CreateXor(CondVal, FalseVal);                               │
│ This ignores the safety of speculatively executing the value substituted into xor. If  │
│ FalseVal is an instruction that is not safe to speculatively execute (can produce      │
│ poison/undef in contexts where select would have avoided it), the transform is illegal │
│ under poison semantics. samesign icmp is one such case.                                │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We should guard the transform with a speculative-execution safety check on the value   │
│ that will be fed to xor. Specifically, only perform the rewrite if FalseVal is either  │
│ a constant or an instruction that isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute. This preserves the     │
│ non-speculative nature of select w.r.t. poison. Edit at InstCombineSelect.cpp line     │
│ ~4156:                                                                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ - Before returning the xor, insert:                                                    │
│   if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(FalseVal))                                       │
│     if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I))                                              │
│       return nullptr;                                                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ This ensures we do not introduce unconditional consumption of a potentially            │
│ poison-producing value.                                                                │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ By guarding the select-to-xor inversion transform with isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute on │
│ the operand substituted into xor, we prevent the introduction of extra poison and      │
│ align with LLVM's semantics that select does not speculatively consume unselected      │
│ operands. This fix addresses the incorrect transformation in the given reproducer and  │
│ similar cases involving poison-sensitive compares such as samesign icmp.               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
